source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to follow, to succeed, to come after in a sequence","examples":[{"text":"قَوْلٌ مَعْرُوفٌ وَمَغْفِرَةٌ خَيْرٌ مِنْ صَدَقَةٍ يَتْبَعُهَا أَذًى","english":"A kind word with forgiveness is better than almsgiving followed by injury."}]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to follow physically, to pursue, to move behind in the same path"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to follow, to adhere to, abide by, or obey; to comply with","examples":[{"text":"فَمَنْ تَبِعَ هُدَايَ فَلَا خَوْفٌ عَلَيْهِمْ وَلَا هُمْ يَحْزَنُونَ","english":"Whosoever follows My guidance, on them shall be no fear, nor shall they grieve."}]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of تَبِعَ (tabiʕa) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"follower(s)","tags":["collective"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"a king in ancient Yemen; the ruler of Himyar and Hadramawt"}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"Uncertain. Lane claims that it is from the root ت ب ع (t b ʕ), in reference to how when one king died, his successor would follow his policies. The unusual plural pattern suggests a borrowing from Old South Arabian, but the cognate root in those languages likely has the same meaning of \"follow\", and is only attested in theophoric names."},"ipa":["/ta.bi.ʕa/"]}